    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3944909680" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3944909680" />
    <a title="Simon SaysWatch" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/49295580-simon-sayswatch"><img alt="Simon SaysWatch" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1448207178p2/49295580.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3944909680?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Simon SaysWatch" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Simon SaysWatch" href="/user/show/49295580-simon-sayswatch">Simon SaysWatch</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3944909680&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3944909680" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15288967088042214456">Hitchhiking through Vietnam and staying at the homes of new acquaintances, I asked about “communism.” The conversation dropped to a whisper. To say the word was to recognize, and so criticize, the system.<br/><br/>In the West, disinformation, as a word that reveals the structure of our own system, is also closed down, smeared as guilty-by-association, turned into “disinformation,” spurious by definition. Everyday life can continue. Proposed Roads to Freedom is a next stop for eyes opened perhaps by Chomsk</span>
  <span id="freeText15288967088042214456" style="display:none">Hitchhiking through Vietnam and staying at the homes of new acquaintances, I asked about “communism.” The conversation dropped to a whisper. To say the word was to recognize, and so criticize, the system.<br /><br />In the West, disinformation, as a word that reveals the structure of our own system, is also closed down, smeared as guilty-by-association, turned into “disinformation,” spurious by definition. Everyday life can continue. Proposed Roads to Freedom is a next stop for eyes opened perhaps by Chomsky, a great admirer of Russell’s, to disinformation serving duopoly democracy that covers for military control towards the upward transfer of wealth worldwide—our own system— and once seeing the system, looking beyond it.<br /><br />Russell’s book is about socialism, anarchism, and syndicalism, all of which “aim at abolishing every kind of privilege and every kind of artificial inequality” though as he says, “whatever bitterness and hate may be found in these movements, it is not bitterness or hate but love that is their wellspring.”<br /><br />A few points to get an idea of the book:<br /><br />Anarchism advocates free sharing, and “civilization and progress compatible with equality (via) production more scientific and better organized (leaving) a comparatively small amount of quite agreeable work to keep the whole population in comfort.”<br /><br />Today’s (2021) increasing automation would, in a non-capitalist system, exactly follow the anarchist model in creating a better life for everyone through progress rather than being better for the tiny few and worse for the mass of people forced into unemployment.<br /><br />Today’s Publix company, by being employee-owned, successfully holds to the anarchist model of industry as “self-governing communities, in which the producers could decide all questions of methods, conditions, hours of work.” Publix was (of course) one of only 4 of the largest 15 US companies to continue offering hazard pay through the pandemic.<br /><br />Syndicalism also rejects the state, but with change “conducted via industrial rather than political methods - strike, boycott, label, and sabotage” such as following the rules to the point that they are unworkable.<br /><br />Though written in 1918, the book only very occasionally betrays its origins before any of the changes of the last over 100 years due to Russell’s enlightened outlook and simultaneously down to earth and twinkle-eyed enquiry.<br /><br />Russell investigates each system, such as critiquing anarchism’s revolt against the military police force of government, maintaining, though, “the power of the state needs to be very carefully scrutinized and every possibility of diminishing its power is to be welcomed provided it doesn’t lead to a private tyranny” (as it has in 2021).<br /><br />On socialism, “Marx does not blame capitalists for the cruelties of which he shows them to be guilty; he merely points out that they are under an inherent necessity to behave cruelly so long as private ownership of land and capital continues.”<br /><br />“The bad effect of the present system on character and the immensely better effect to be expected from communal ownership, are among the strongest reasons for advocating change.”<br /><br />“To stop the hoarding of money which could produce capitalists”, combining Russell’s suggestion and an example from today, money could be like holiday days, only available for use over a particular period.<br /><br />“Unpleasant jobs - people could be attracted into these by higher pay or shorter hours instead of being driven into them.”<br /><br />Russell’s welcome bursts of humor are present: “People...might have supposed the duties of a magistrate would be among disagreeable trades, like cleaning sewers; but a cynic might contend that the pleasures of vindictiveness and moral superiority are so great that there is no difficulty in finding well-to-do elderly gentlemen who are willing, without pay, to send helpless wretches to the torture of prison.”<br /><br />Perhaps best of all in Proposed Roads to Freedom, worthy of Chomsky over a half century before time, is Russell’s tangent on international relations and the press (and China): <br /><br />“The main objects which should be served by international relations may be taken to be two: First, the avoidance of wars, and, second, the (avoidance of the) oppression of weak nations by strong ones.”<br /><br />“These two objects do not by any means necessarily lead in the same direction, since one of the easiest ways of securing the world’s peace would be by a combination of the world’s powerful states for the exploitation and oppression of the remainder.”<br /><br />“Socialistic and Anarchistic critics of existing society point, with perfect truth, to certain capitalistic factors which promote war. The first of these is the desire to finance new fields of investment in underdeveloped countries.”<br /><br />“The ever-growing need for fresh fields of investment for their profits is the great crux of the financial system.”<br /><br />“To minimize risks, the financiers call in the assistance of the military and naval forces. In order to have the support of public opinion in this demand they have recourse to the power of the Press.”<br /><br />“The Press is the second great factor to which critics of capitalism point when they wish to prove that capitalism is the source of modern war. Since the running of a big newspaper requires a large capital, the proprietors of important organs necessarily belong to the capitalist class, and it will be a rare and exceptional event if they do not sympathize with their own class in opinion and outlook.”<br /><br />“They are able to decide what news the great mass of newspaper readers shall be allowed to have. They can actually falsify the news, or, without going so far as that, they can carefully select it, giving such items as will stimulate the passions which they desire to stimulate.”<br /><br />“In this way, the picture of the world in the mind of the average newspaper reader is made to be not a true picture, but in the main that which suits the interests of capitalists.”<br /><br />“This is true above all in what concerns the relations between nations. The mass of the population of a country can be led to love or hate any other country at the will of the newspaper proprietors, which is often directly or indirectly by the will of the great financiers.”<br /><br />“China as a field of general industrial development already begins to loom large in the eyes of foresighted American businessmen...Diplomatic pressure, armed force, and, where desirable, seizure of territory for political control, will be engineered by the financial magnates who control the political destiny of America.”<br /><br />US public opinion on China which held steady for decades has dipped precipitously over just the last couple of years (by 2021) due to stories originating with religious fundamentalists. Adrian Zenz’s and the designated terrorist group, ETIM, the East Turkestan Islamic Movement’s self-serving statements on Uighur “concentration camps” and “genocide” are covered uncritically by the press closely following Russell’s outline.<br /><br />So, a long review and coverage of a book only 179 pages long reflecting its value today, as ever, and still leaving over 175 pages to discover of Bertrand Russell, this great mind and big heart.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15288967088042214456" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


