<div id="review_2143751258" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2143751258" />
    <a title="Cinderella Diab" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27657357-cinderella-diab"><img alt="Cinderella Diab" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609650188p2/27657357.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2143751258?book_show_action=true">Oct 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cinderella Diab" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cinderella Diab" href="/user/show/27657357-cinderella-diab">Cinderella Diab</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27657357-cinderella-diab?shelf=audio-books">audio-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2143751258" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16245137134472490535">I always felt that when Marx and Anglez thought of writing the Communist Manifesto he was feeling angry from seeing people working in an unfair work environments. Communism and Capitalism are completely the opposite directions of each other. And each determines to destroy the other to live. As extremism controls the situation I cannot see a better way to live unless unleashing the power of Anarchism. <br/><br/>However in the chapter two, I changed my mind. Violence is not pretext that we can easily surpas</span>
  <span id="freeText16245137134472490535" style="display:none">I always felt that when Marx and Anglez thought of writing the Communist Manifesto he was feeling angry from seeing people working in an unfair work environments. Communism and Capitalism are completely the opposite directions of each other. And each determines to destroy the other to live. As extremism controls the situation I cannot see a better way to live unless unleashing the power of Anarchism. <br /><br />However in the chapter two, I changed my mind. Violence is not pretext that we can easily surpass because of its capability of happening in every doctrine. We think to make it better not to neglect our vices. It is true that violence is an integral part of our nature. But we have to solve that. Now there are societies proving that violence can be treated. Countries has closed their prisons for prisoners lack. <br />On the other hand they were escaping from the overwork hours and slavery which could have been achieved without changing the economic system. I know.. shock treatment is better than ever in those situations, especially ideas like sharing the properties or getting rid of any kind of social obligation were brand new to them. <br /><br />"The economic organization of society as conceived by anarchist communist does not differ greatly from that which is sort by socialist. Their difference from socialists is in the manner of government; they demand that the government shall require the consent of all the governed and not only of the majority. It is undeniable that the rule of the majority may be almost as hostile to freedom as the rule of the minority. " <br />As ideal as it seems, unfortunately it is impossible to be achieved practically. Each of the governed conceive his own visualization of the status quo regime. It is not a matter of persuasion anymore unless the vile strategies of public speech psychology are used to control them. Then it does not differ from capitalism. <br /><br />"Syndicalists aim at using the strike not to secure such improvements of detail as employers make rent but to destroy the whole system of employer and employed and win the complete emancipation of the worker" <br />"Capitalism has made of work a purely commercial activity, a soulless and joyless thing." <br />"Syndicalists consider man as producer rather than a consumer. They are more concerned to procure freedom to work than to increase material well being. They have revived the quest for liberty which has grown somewhat dimmed under the regime of parliamentary socialism and they have reminded men that what are modern society needs is not a little tinkering key here and there nor the kind of minor readjustments to which the existing holder of power may consent but fundamental reconstruction, a sweeping away of all the sources of oppression, a liberation of men, constructive energies and holly new way of conceiving and regularly reproduction and economic relation." <br /><br />As i see from the above quotes that the syndicalism only cares about the worker not the employer. I agree on that totally. But what I conceive from all that is every doctrine came as a reaction of vile management of the predecessor. If the Capitalism was not controlled by greed, manipulation and exploitation Socialism would never have been thought of. Likewise about the Socialism, if it had been executed fairly, people would not have had the mere idea of demanding for the legal and righteous rights. I am not sure. I just feel that the proletariat classes were taken advantage of really good in the course of the human history. This endless vicious circle of defending the rights of the poor workers against the greed of the employers is making me mad. We still do not learn of our history. Unbelievable! <br /><br />Okay I think I am driven to the Anarchism regarding work and play. I have to say I still do not believe in the free sharing policy nor in the free driven work; some nations won't stand on their legs if you told them you do not have to work. Unfortunately what i see is that Anarchism is supposing that man is naturally good. I have problem with that. He is not naturally good. Hence not obligating him to work in the name of freedom and enjoying life and to share properties and DAMN, BOY, HAVE FUN!!! no. But still I have decided to read about Anarchism. I need a more profound and intimate view added to this.<br /><br />And finally thanks for LIBRVOX for giving me such opportunity.. you guys make hell of a work, so thank you. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16245137134472490535" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


