    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2452233527" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2452233527" />
    <a title="Shanna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57849548-shanna"><img alt="Shanna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468957731p2/57849548.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2452233527?book_show_action=true">Jan 27, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shanna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shanna" href="/user/show/57849548-shanna">Shanna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2452233527" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7260559933919520523">I thought Russell explored Socialism and Anarchism very well and very fairly. His aim in the book is to find an economic and political system that brings the greatest freedom. However, he fails to take into account mankind&apos;s nature and this kept frustrating me- nothing he talked about seemed plausible. He puts too much faith in the nature of man and thinks all men could be good and sustain an ideal society. Has he never seen children fighting over what does not belong to them before they can eve</span>
  <span id="freeText7260559933919520523" style="display:none">I thought Russell explored Socialism and Anarchism very well and very fairly. His aim in the book is to find an economic and political system that brings the greatest freedom. However, he fails to take into account mankind's nature and this kept frustrating me- nothing he talked about seemed plausible. He puts too much faith in the nature of man and thinks all men could be good and sustain an ideal society. Has he never seen children fighting over what does not belong to them before they can even talk? He clearly falls on the nurture side of the nature v. nurture debate and he believes humanity can be taught a better way through education and kinder circumstances. Granted, both of these could help in some cases, but, as Kant proposed, greater wisdom and knowledge can be an evil if one's will is evil as it will better enable that will toward evil. Even if Russell were correct, the system he proposes requires some to be in power by default, just to keep the system maintained and controlled, and he acknowledges that power tends to corrupt. No matter what, we end up with corrupt rulers. Men are corrupt- this must be assumed to have any legitimacy and practicality to any economic or political theory.<br /><br />Russell has a problem outside of his terrible misjudgment of humanity's nature, and that is having a practical, possible, sustainable economic system that gives freedom and is not Capitalism. His proposed solution is a form of Guild Socialism, which actually has similar to aspects of American capitalism today, such as welfare or free education up to a certain age. (I admit the welfare system is incredibly imperfect but it is the same idea Russell proposes- everyone has a minimum of what they need.) Russell's definition of freedom is a "[reduction] to the lowest possible point the interference of one man with the life of another" and neither Socialism nor Anarchism give this (119). Socialism does not offer this because the state becomes all-powerful and oppressive. Anarchism could offer this except it is unreachable. Even if it were to be reached, everyone must agree and conform. In either case (and Russell points this out as well, see chapter 7 "Science and Art under Socialism") the system would not allow alternate views to be expressed in the arts, science, or theories of philosophy and economics. See Orwell's 1984. So we come back to Guild Socialism, his proposed middle ground, where guilds and labor groups create local control (another ideal of democracy in America). Russell is writing from a time in which class struggles were much more pervasive and the middle class was still very new. I wonder what he would think or how his ideas would change post WWII, post labor laws and the rights of workers.<br /><br />Overall, I thought his ideas outdated or too idealistic, and I cannot find it possible that humanity could be altruistic enough to pull itself out of its current state, create an ideal society, and then maintain it. Anyway, I would be curious to see how his ideas changed even 5o years after writing this or what he would speculate had he a more realistic view of mankind. Most important, however, is the litmus test for freedom he has provided: that a society is free when those within it have the freedom to disagree.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7260559933919520523" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

